article.headline: UMKC 73, Valparaiso 70
article.story: KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) -- Quinton Day scored a career-high 37 points, including a 22-footer with 2.7 seconds left, to lift Missouri-Kansas City past Valparaiso 73-70 on Thursday night. Day helped the Kangaroos overcome double-digit deficits in both halves, scoring all 17 of his first-half points during a 25-9 run that gave UMKC a 36-33 lead after falling behind 24-11. Valparaiso ended the first half with an 8-1 run of its own to take a 41-37 lead at the break. The Crusaders (16-10, 8-7) were plagued by poor free-throw shooting in the second half, going 3-of-9 from the stripe. Valparaiso was led by Dan Oppland with 20 points, followed by Ron Howard with 15, Jimmie Miles with 11 and Ali Berdiel with 10. Kalu Guasco added 14 points for UMKC (13-13, 10-5). Valparaiso opened the second half with a 11-2 run that put the Crusaders up 54-39 with 13:02 left in the game. But a 22-4 UMKC run over the next 7:40 erased the Valparaiso lead, putting the Kangaroos up 61-58 with 5:22 remaining. After Berdiel hit a 3-pointer for the Crusaders to tie the game at 70-70 with 24.6 seconds left, Day ran the clock down to about 7 seconds and used a screen to get open for the game-winner. With the win, the Kangaroos clinched the third seed in the Mid-Continent Conference tournament March 4-7 in Tulsa. They will play in the 8:30 p.m. game March 5. Valparaiso must beat Oral Roberts on the road or have Southern Utah lose at home to either Oakland or IUPUI to claim the fourth spot in the conference tournament.
